courses.learning_outcomes:
1. Able to understanding of the basics concept of rock mechanics: physical and mechanic properties of rock and rock mass, intact rock failure mode and failure criteria, the shear criteria for jointed rock, initial stresses under the ground in rocks and their measurement; and rock deformation under loading;
2. Able to apply the basic principles of rock mechanics to solve problems in rock engineering projects, such as rock slope, rock tunnel and rock foundation;
3. Able to perform assessments and professional judgment on the safety or possible failure of complex rock engineering projects;
4. Able to exercise professional judgment in the evaluation and justification of possible failure in complex rock engineering projects;
5. Able to have critical and creative thinking in solving rock engineering problems and have an ability to work independently.

At the completion of this course, the students will be able to

1) Gain fundamental concepts of the general circulations of the atmosphere and oceans;

2) Understand how they are simulated in climate models;

3) Develop the ability to analyze and explain climate phenomena, including human-related climate change, based on climate modelling results.

(Course outcomes as related to Programme Learning Outcomes) -- The students will develop: 1) the ability to evaluate an issue critically based on evidence and scientific principle, 2) to acquire knowledge effectively by self-study and using information technology, and to work independently, 3) to work effectively in a team, and 4) to present information in a clear, concise and logical manner. The students also can acquire a responsible attitude in study and work, and have motivation for life-long learning.

Students are expected to gain the following abilities:
1. Understand the relationships between materials, processes and landforms;
2. Use concepts of solid and fluid mechanics to interpret the formation of landforms;
3. Use graphical tools to compile and interpret field and laboratory data;
4. Integrate topics in mineralogy, petrology, structural geology, plate tectonics, climate sciences, biogeosciences, hydrology, remote sensing and geotechnical engineering through survey of scientific literature, case studies, books and textbooks; and
5. Make primary observations in the field and using them to construct and test hypotheses.

Lectures focus on physical and chemical aspects of landform evolution and understanding spatial patterns in landscapes and how humans affect and are impacted by Earth surface processes. Labs use the geological maps, terrain classification maps, aerial photography interpretation, societal consequence assessment, and physical models to illustrate these concepts.
Students are encouraged to ask, follow-up research and lead discussion of questions regarding lecture topics throughout the semester. Field trips in the second half of the semester encourage small-group discussion of observations and interpretations of landscape evolution and human impacts in mountainous and coastal terrains.
The students will develop the ability: 1) to evaluate an issue critically based on evidence and
scientific principles, 2) to acquire knowledge effectively by self-study and using information technology, and to work independently, 3) to work effectively in a team, and 4) to present information in a clear, concise and logical manner. The students will also be challenged to manage a large amount of reading in short periods of time and to think of their role as a citizen and in society.

Students are expected to attain the knowledge about how urbanisation affects the local climate and the underlying processes. They should also be able to:
1. describe the scientific processes and explain the theories of how urbanisation alters local climate;
2. explain the physical mechanisms governing the formation of urban climatic phenomena;
3. conduct numerical modelling and field experiments of urban climatic processes; and
4. understand the practical implications of urban climatology on climate-sensitive urban planning and design.
